{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"71"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/71"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0.65,0.16,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"71"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98744"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/71"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"71"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81135"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98744"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic to discuss contraceptive options as she is in a new sexual relationship. She has regular periods which last 4-5 days, during which she needs to change her pad every two hours. She finds this heavy bleeding intolerable and experiences significant pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes an emergency appendicectomy two years ago, and a partial seizure disorder for which she has recently been started on carbamazepine. She has not had any previous sexually transmitted infections. During her appendicectomy admission, she had a pelvic ultrasound which showed a small right-sided ovarian cyst, no uterine wall distortion, and normal endometrial thickness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a well-healed appendicectomy scar with no tenderness or masses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following contraceptive options would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progestogen implant","Progesterone-only pill","Levonorgestrel intrauterine device","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Copper intrauterine device"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires contraception while taking carbamazepine and also has heavy menstrual bleeding that needs to be addressed. The most appropriate option is the \u003Cstrong\u003Elevonorgestrel intrauterine device \u003C/strong\u003E(e.g. \u0027Mirena\u0027), which provides reliable contraception that is not affected by enzyme-inducing medications while also reducing menstrual blood loss. The levonorgestrel intrauterine device works primarily through local effects on the endometrium, causing endometrial atrophy and reduced menstrual bleeding. It also thickens cervical mucus, inhibits sperm motility and function, and may inhibit ovulation in some women. These effects make it over 99% effective as a contraceptive method.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogestogen implant\u003C/strong\u003E (i.e. \u0027Implanon\u0027) is normally a highly effective long-acting reversible contraceptive, but its efficacy is significantly reduced by enzyme-inducing medications like carbamazepine. Carbamazepine induces cytochrome P450 enzymes in the liver, which accelerate the metabolism of hormonal contraceptives, reducing their effectiveness. This makes the implant an unsuitable choice for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogesterone-only pill\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly affected by carbamazepine\u0027s enzyme-inducing properties. Its efficacy would be substantially reduced, making it an unreliable contraceptive option for this patient. Additionally, it would not adequately address her heavy menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be considered for heavy menstrual bleeding, but like other systemic hormonal methods, its effectiveness is compromised by carbamazepine. The accelerated metabolism of ethinylestradiol and progestogens would significantly reduce its contraceptive efficacy and its ability to control menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecopper intrauterine device\u003C/strong\u003E is not affected by enzyme-inducing medications and would provide reliable contraception. However, it is associated with increased menstrual blood loss and dysmenorrhoea, which would likely worsen this patient\u0027s already problematic heavy bleeding. Therefore, while it would address the contraceptive needs, it would exacerbate her menstrual symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the levonorgestrel intrauterine device is the optimal choice as it provides reliable contraception that is not affected by enzyme-inducing medications while simultaneously addressing the patient\u0027s heavy menstrual bleeding. It is important to note that women taking enzyme-inducing medications should be counselled about the potential for reduced efficacy of hormonal contraceptives and advised about alternative methods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding the small ovarian cyst noted on her ultrasound, this is likely a physiological or functional cyst. Small ovarian cysts (typically \u003C3 cm) are commonly found incidentally on pelvic imaging in women of reproductive age and represent normal ovarian function during the menstrual cycle. These physiological cysts usually resolve spontaneously within 1-2 menstrual cycles and do not require specific management or follow-up unless they are symptomatic, large, or have concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The levonorgestrel intrauterine system is an effective contraceptive option that is also used to treat heavy menstrual bleeding and dysmenorrhoea","Carbamazepine is a potent hepatic enzyme inducer and will reduce the efficacy of systemic hormonal contraception","Intrauterine contraceptive methods are not affected by enzyme-inducing medications"],"references":["Bateson D, McNamee K. Intrauterine Contraception: A best practice approach across the reproductive lifespan. MedicineToday. 2016.;17(3):55-61. Available at: https://medicinetoday.com.au/mt/2016/march/regular-series/intrauterine-contraception-best-practice-approach-across-reproductive-lifespan","Grandi G, Farulla A, Sileo FG, Facchinetti F. Levonorgestrel-releasing intra-uterine systems as female contraceptives.\u00a0Expert Opin Pharmacother. 2018;19(7):677-686. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29637798/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81135"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"71"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81135"},"attributes":{"crea